<dl id="n12213j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12213j">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12213j"> 213(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Homer sung at Panathenae</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>La r&eacute;citation des po&egrave;mes hom&eacute;riques aux Panath&eacute;n&eacute;es</mark> n&apos;&eacute;tait probablement ni un hommage &agrave; leur beaut&eacute;, ni un divertissement festival imagin&eacute; par un homme de go&ucirc;t; mais elle avait un sens religieux et politique. <br><font color="green">[The recitation of Homeric poems at the Panathenae was probably neither an homage to their beauty nor a festive pastime organized by a man of good taste; they had a religious and a political meaning]</font> <small> Stefan Czarnowski, <a name="SCSP" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SCSP"><cite title="source">Le culte des h&eacute;ros et ses conditions sociale: saint Patrick, h&eacute;ros nationale de l'Irlande</cite></a> (1919) XLIX-L</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
